Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Helmuth, Ingeborg, Johann.","North German and Dutch: patronymic from   Willer  .","English (Cambridgeshire, Lincolnshire, and Essex): variant of   Willer  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Willer","meanings":["German and Dutch: from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>heri</i> ‘army’.","English: variant of   Weller  .","English: perhaps in some cases an occupational name from a shortened form of <i>Willyer</i>, now extinct, but derived from Middle English <i>wilier</i> ‘one who works in willow’, a derivative of Middle English <i>wily</i> (Old English <i>wilige</i>) ‘willow’ + <i>-er</i> ‘worker in willow’, probably a maker of baskets or hurdles."]}]},{"name":"Ermeline","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, introduced to Britain by the Normans. In origin it seems to have been a derivative of   Emma  , but when it was revived in the 19th century there was some confusion with   Emily .  It was born by the suffragette  Emmeline Pankhurst  (  1858–1928 ), mother of  Christabel  and  Sylvia ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"\"Emma\"","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, originally a short form of compound names such as   Ermintrude   containing the word <i>erm(en)</i>, <i>irm(en)</i> ‘entire’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, but its popularity in medieval England was greatly enhanced by the fact that it had been borne by the mother of Edward the Confessor, herself a Norman. In modern times, it was only in moderate use early in the 20th century but rose sharply in favour in the 1970s and has since remained perennially popular.